pullRequest.body:
Add lemmas necessary to prove simplicial complex results in elementary terms

---
This is a WIP PR and should not be evaluated at this time. I am pushing it so that another author has easy access to it, but I am currently on holiday and am unable to prepare it for merging at this time.

It is a refactored and improved version of #9145, which is now mostly (but not entirely) redundant.

It is possible that this PR will be broken up in turn due to the noted WIP nature.

This PR/issue depends on:

* ~~leanprover-community/mathlib4#10163~~
By **[Dependent Issues](https://github.com/z0al/dependent-issues)** (ðŸ¤–). Happy coding!
<!-- By Dependent Issues (Action) - DO NOT REMOVE -->
Great, that's useful. I think there might be some inequality ones about predAbove - can you remind me what is there?

The inequality results currently in the OrderHom file are 

- `predAbove p i < p â†” i < castSucc p`, 
- `p â‰¤ predAbove p i â†” castSucc p â‰¤ i`
- `predAbove p i â‰¤ p â†” i â‰¤ succ p`

i.e. those involving just `p` and `i`. There doesn't appear to be anything with a third variable.
Right, yes, I see the issue. Presumably there would also be equivalent results with succAbove.

Fundamentally what we need is something like p.predAbove i <= castPred i, because then there's a lemma that converts i<= castSucc j into castPred i< j. So I see how you do the proof but I agree that some kind of lemma would be useful.

There are some results (that I had at one point but removed) that are something like p.predAbove i<= j iff i <= succAbove (succAbove i p) _, can't quite remember what goes there. It's like the predAbove_eq_iff result basically. I don't know if that would be useful.

> Fundamentally what we need is something like p.predAbove i <= castPred i, because then there's a lemma that converts i<= castSucc j into castPred i< j. So I see how you do the proof but I agree that some kind of lemma would be useful.

Or something like `(p.predAbove i).castSucc <= i`. Then one can get `(p.predAbove i).castSucc <=j.castSucc`, and then from the monotone property  (p.predAbove i)<= j.

Yes, I've been thinking actually about many properties about predAbove being better stated by wrapping them like that (you often don't really want to work with pred and castPred directly). I think that's a good idea.

For the other lemmas we would need `i <= (p.predAbove i).succ`. If `j.succ <= i`, then one gets `j.succ<= (p.predAbove i).succ`

The corresponding succAbove results (avoiding pred and castPred) would be `i.castSucc<=(p.succAbove i)` and `(p.succAbove i) <= i.succ`
